      {
        "paragraph_index": 2,
        "text": "### Chemistry Insight\n\nThis result is a textbook illustration of **HSAB (Hard-Soft Acid-Base) theory**. Thiocyanate coordinates through its soft sulfur donor to soft metal ions. Hg²⁺ is the softest of the three d-block/p-block cations, so it forms an exceptionally strong Hg–SCN bond (log K₁ ≈ 9.6). Cd²⁺ is borderline-soft and binds moderately, while Pb²⁺ — a harder borderline acid — shows the weakest interaction. The very large, negative ΔH for Hg²⁺ (−49 kJ/mol at I = 0) confirms that the driving force is predominantly enthalpic, consistent with strong covalent Hg–S bonding.",
        "claims": [
          {
            "start": 0,
            "end": 21,
            "text": "### Chemistry Insight",
